Because $\lfloor a - 1/2\rfloor=\lfloor a\rfloor-1$ for real $a$,we have $\lfloor\lfloor 2x\rfloor-1/2\rfloor=\lfloor\lfloor 2x\rfloor\rfloor-1=\lfloor 2x\rfloor-1$. Also,if $m\in\mathbb Z$,then
\begin{align*}\lfloor 2x\rfloor -1\geq \lfloor x+2\rfloor& \Leftrightarrow \text{$2x\geq m+1$,and if $m$ even,then $x+2\geq m+2$}\\\\ &\Leftrightarrow \text{$x\geq \frac 12$,and if $m$ even,then $x\geq\frac m2$}.\end{align*}
We divide into cases: suppose $x\geq 1$. Then if $m$ is even, $f(x)=m-3$. We have\begin{align*}\text{if $m\geq 3$ and even,then we have no solutions}\\ \text{if $m=2$,then $f(x)=2-3=-1$, so $x=1-1/2=1/2$},\\ \text{if $m=1$,then $f(x)=1-3=-2$,so that $x=1/2$},\\ \text{and if $m$ is odd,then $f(x)=m-3$, so $x\geq (m-3)/2$}.\end{align*}
Suppose $1/2<x<1$. Then if $m$ is even,$f(x)=m-3$. We have\begin{align*}\text{if $m\geq 5$ and even,then $f(x)=m-3\geq 5-3=2$,so no solutions.}\\ \text{if $m=3$,then $f(x)=3-3=0$,so that $x=2/2=1$, a contradiction}\\ \text{if $m=2$,then $f(x)=2-3=-1$,so that $x=1/2$, a contradiction}\\ \text{and if $m$ is odd,then $f(x)=m-3$, so $x\geq (m-3)/2$}.\end{align*}
Suppose $0\leq x<1/2$. Then we have either $-1\leq 2x<1$, so $-2\leq \lfloor 2x\rfloor <-1$, so the LHS is $-2$, but then $2\leq \lfloor x+2\rfloor$ would force $f(x)=-1$, and if $x>0$ then LHS would be $=0$, so no solutions. \end{align*}
In summary, no matter what we choose $x$, we will have either $f(x)=-2$, or $f(x)=-1$. Equivalently,$\lfloor \lfloor 2x\rfloor-1/2\rfloor=\lfloor \lfloor 2x\rfloor -\frac 12 \rfloor=-(\lfloor 2x\rfloor +1)$.
